  "opinion": "As a woman who's been working in Chicago's construction industry for over thirty years, I've seen firsthand how science and engineering often feel out of reach for people like me. The gender gap in science isn't just about numbers—it's about the quiet messages that tell girls and women early on that they don't belong in labs or engineering fields. My parents didn't have college degrees, so I never had the same access to STEM resources that many of my peers did. I've seen too many talented women in my community get discouraged because they're not sure if they're 'smart enough' for science. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. I've volunteered at local science fairs and try to encourage girls to pursue STEM by showing them that science isn't just for 'the boys'—it's for everyone. We need to create more mentorship opportunities that are accessible to people without formal education or advanced degrees, like myself. It's not about fixing the problem overnight; it's about building bridges where women feel they can belong without having to prove themselves over and over again. I worry about the anxiety that comes with being the only woman in a room full of men who don't understand your perspective. But when you make space for people who've been told they don't belong, science becomes something that everyone can contribute to.",
